V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a| region           = [[Western Philosophy]]\u000a| era              = [[Contemporary philosophy]]\u000a| image       = \u000a| image_size       =\u000a| caption     = \u000a| birth_name       = \u000a| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1946|6|13}}\u000a| birth_place      = \u000a| death_date       =\u000a| school_tradition = [[Virtue Ethics]]\u000a| main_interests   = \u000a| notable_ideas    = \u000a| influences       = [[Aristotle]]{{·}}[[Plato]]{{·}}[[Sextus Empiricus]]{{·}}[[Cicero]]{{·}}[[Seneca the Younger|Seneca]]{{·}}[[Epicurus]]{{·}}[[Philodemus]]{{·}}[[Philippa Foot]]{{·}}[[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]]\u000a| alma_mater       = [[Oxford University]]\u000a| institutions     = [[University of Arizona]]\u000a| influenced       =\u000a| signature        =\u000a}}\u000a'''Julia Elizabeth Annas''' (born 1946)<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780-2010: Chapter A|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterA.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> is a British [[philosopher]] who has taught in the United States for the last quarter-century. She is [[Regents Professor]] of Philosophy at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>[http://philosophy.arizona.edu/julia-annas Julia Annas at the University of Arizona]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Biography==\u000aAnnas graduated from [[Oxford University]] in 1968 with a B.A., and from [[Harvard University]]  with an A.M. (1970) and a  Ph.D. (1972).<ref>http://www.u.arizona.edu/~jannas/</ref> She was a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Fellow]] and Tutor at [[St Hugh's College, Oxford]] for fifteen years, before joining the faculty at Arizona in 1986, where she has taught since, apart for one year as a professor at Columbia University. She concentrates on the study of ancient [[Greek philosophy]], including [[Ethics]], [[Psychology]] and [[Epistemology]]. \u000aHer current research interests are in Platonic ethics. She was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1992,<ref name=AAAS /> and a Fellow of the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2013.<ref>https://www.amphilsoc.org/members/electedApril2013</ref>  She is the founder and former editor of the annual journal, ''Oxford Studies in Ancient Philosophy''.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DmNNb_rcX1YC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Julia+Annas+oxford&source=bl&ots=XGP4zpmH-v&sig=e31Dna25-74RJhU7pjtIJJyjBIM&hl=en&ei=ILl6S8SrJY-3ngerxbiwCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=&f=false| title=Oxford studies in ancient philosophy, Volume 20| editor=Julia Annas| publisher=Oxford University Press| year= 2001| isbn= 978-0-19-924225-2 | first=David | last=Sedley}}</ref>  She is married to the Hume scholar, David Owen, also a professor of philosophy at the University of Arizona.\u000a\u000a==Philosophy==\u000aJulia Annas has advocated ethics based on [[Virtue Ethics|character]], building on ideas attributed to [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] philosopher, [[Aristotle]] and making them relevant for contemporary moral discourse.<ref>A detailed account of her philosophical approach is set out in her 2011 book, Intelligent Virtue; an academic synopsis of the book is available [http://philpapers.org/rec/ANNIV here]</ref>  She has argued that being virtuous involves \u201cpractical reasoning\u201d<ref name="here">For more on this, see Julia Annas\u2019 article from \u2018Phenomenology and the Cognitive Sciences, 2008, accessible [http://philpapers.org/rec/ANNTPO here]</ref> which can be compared to the \u201cexercising of a practical skill\u201d.  Hence, she argues, rather than relating virtues to rules, principles, or an end goal, Annas says, first, people should ask how they can improve their moral \u201cskills\u201d.<ref name="here"/>\u000a\u000a==Major writings==\u000a\u000a===Books===\u000a*''Intelligent Virtue'' (Oxford, 2011).\u000a*''Plato: A Very Short Introduction'' (Oxford, 2003).\u000a*''Ancient Philosophy: A Very Short Introduction'' (Oxford, 2000).\u000a*''Voices of Ancient Philosophy: An Introductory Reader'' (Oxford, 2000).\u000a*''Platonic Ethics, Old and New'' (Cornell, 1999).\u000a*{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KRfwSjk3fBcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Julia+Annas&cd=1#v=onepage&q=&f=false| title=The Morality of Happiness| year= 1993| publisher=Oxford University Press | first=Julia | last=Annas | isbn=978-0-19-509652-1}}  (reprint 1995, ISBN 978-0-19-509652-1)\u000a*''Hellenistic Philosophy of Mind'' (California, 1992).\u000a*''The Modes of Scepticism'' (Cambridge, 1985), with [[Jonathan Barnes]].\u000a*''An Introduction to Plato's Republic'' (Oxford, 1981).\u000a*''Aristotle's Metaphysics, Books M and N, translated with introduction and notes, (Oxford 1976).\u000a\u000a===Translations===\u000a*[[Plato]], ''Statesman'' (Cambridge, 1995), with [[Robin Waterfield]].\u000a*[[Sextus Empiricus]], ''Outlines of Scepticism'' (Cambridge, 1994), with [[Jonathan Barnes]].\u000a*[[Aristotle]], ''Aristotle's Metaphysics Books M and N'' (Oxford, 1976).\u000a\u000a===Recent articles===\u000a*"What are Plato\u2019s \u201cMiddle\u201d Dialogues in the Middle Of?" (Harvard University Press, 2002)\u000a*"Democritus and Eudaimonism" (Presocratic Philosophy: Essays in Honour of Alex Mourelatos, edited by Victor Caston and Daniel Graham, Ashgate, Aldershot, 2002)\u000a*"Aristotle and Kant on Morality and Practical Reasoning" (Aristotle, Kant & The Stoics,ed. S. Ergstrom and J. Whiting, Cambridge 1996)\u000a*"Virtue and Eudaimonism" (Virtue and Vice, ed. E. Paul, J. Jaul and F. Miller,  Cambridge, 1998)\u000a*"Prudence and Morality in Ancient and Modern Ethics" (Ethics, January 1995)\u000a*"Epicurus on Agency" (Passions and Perceptions, Cambridge, 1993)\u000a*"The Good Life and the Good Lives of Others" (The Good Life and the Human Good, Cambridge, 1992)\u000a*"Plato the Sceptic" (Oxford Studies in Ancient Philosophy, Supp. Vol., 1992).\u000a*"Plato's Myths of Judgement" (Phronesis Vol. 27 No. 2, 1982; pp.&nbsp;119\u2013143).\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a*[[American philosophy]]\u000a*[[List of American philosophers]]\u000a*[[Sigmund H. Danziger, Jr. Memorial Lecture in the Humanities]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a*[http://www.u.arizona.edu/~jannas/ Author's website] (Her website includes several [http://www.u.arizona.edu/~jannas/forth/set.htm downloadable articles])]\u000a*[http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/1994/94.06.09.html Review of ''Morality of Happiness'']\u000a*[http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/25503-intelligent-virtue/ Review of ''Intelligent Virtue'']\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Annas, Julia}}\u000a[[Category:1946 births]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:British women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Scholars of ancient Greek philosophy]]\u000a[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of St Hugh's College, Oxford]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\u000a[[Category:Scholars of ancient philosophy]]\u000a[[Category:American women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:British philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]
